entry.title: Convert ArcScreenCaptureSession to use RasterInterface
entry.content:
ArcScreenCaptureSession was using GLES2Interface+GLHelper to capture the

contents of a display and copy that into an ARC++ texture. This is the

last usage of GLES2Interface from the browser process which we want to

eliminate.



Currently a CopyOutputRequest captures the contents of the display at

display size and returns the texture to ArcScreenCaptureSession.

GLHelper was used to scale to the desired size while copying into the

entry.title: Avoid duplicate block-in-inline break tokens.
entry.content:
Regardless of whether the break inside a block-in-inline was to be

resumed in a parallel flow or not, we'd also include it as a break token

in the same flow.



This was usually harmless, since any next line in the same fragmentainer

would typically not be a block-in-inline, since all consecutive blocks

inside inlines are put inside the same block-in-inline wrapper during

box generation.



However, there are ways to end up with adjacent block-in-inline

wrappers: If a block that previously wasn't inflow becomes inflow

(change from float:left to float:none, for instance), a new wrapper is

created around the now-inflow block, even if there's already an adjacent

wrapper there for an adjacent block.













This generates a box tree like this:



LayoutInline SPAN

LayoutNGBlockFlow (floating) DIV #first

LayoutNGBlockFlow (anonymous)

LayoutNGBlockFlow DIV #second



If we (after initial layout) change #first to float:none, we end up with

this:



LayoutInline SPAN

LayoutNGBlockFlow (anonymous)

LayoutNGBlockFlow DIV #first

LayoutNGBlockFlow (anonymous)

LayoutNGBlockFlow DIV #second



The fix is to make sure that we only create one break token for a

fragmented block wrapper. Move the code that examines the outgoing

block-in-inline break token a bit further up, to eliminate the need for

LineInfo::BlockInInlineBreakToken(), and to keep things a bit more

tightly together. Add a DCHECK to LineBreaker::HandleBlockInInline(),

which would have failed without this fix.

AutofillTable. This CL adds the corresponding UpdateProfile() call

via the PDM whenever new observations are collected on form submit.

entry.title: [DBSC] Disable the reconcilor if DBSC is enabled for dogfood
entry.content:
The reconcilor needs to be disabled for the following reasons:

/ListAccounts is not throttled on startup on SIDTS presence. There is a

chance as of today /ListAccounts's response will be impacted by session

binding and missing SIDTS cookie.



This might lead to the reconcilor being triggered to make an

OAuthMultiLogin call. This will either result in terminating a bound

session or a reconcilor loop if OAuthMultiLogin judges no changes to the

session is required. Both are undesirable states.



To avoid adding complexity and extra cases to debug due to reconcilor

OAuthMultiLogin, we will disable the reconcilor for Dogfood Phase 1A

launch with the plans to add support in the next milestone.

entry.content:
ScopedPrerenderContentBrowserClient was introduced by

https://crrev.com/c/4680866 to run browser tests for

prerender-into-new-tab. The client injected

if a valid PrerenderWebContentsDelegate instance exists before accessing

it so the tests no longer need to fake them using

ScopedPrerenderContentBrowserClient.

entry.content:
This is a reland of commit c444bc166b65c35269476ec50411807ed086534c



The original change was causing a compilation error in some builds,

as the argument inside the DCHECKs refers to IsInitializedUserDataDir,

which is not declared/defined in non-debug builds.

- The complex !defined(NDEBUG) || defined(DCHECK_ALWAYS_ON) condition

to the more readable DCHECK_IS_ON().

the previously mentioned compilation errors.

entry.title: Skip closing ShellSurfaceBase if capture mode is active.
entry.content:
It also updates `ash::~Shell` to fix a pre-existing issue that global

instance of `CaptureModeController` sometimes get accessed its

destruction.



Without this change what can happen is that:

- `views::MenuHost` has a capture.

- Chrome starts shutdown and `ash::~Shell` starts. First

`CaptureModeController` is destroyed.

= Then `ash::Shell::CloseAllRootWindowChildWindows` is called which

causes the `MenuHost` to lose capture and call

`MenuHost::OnMouseCaptureLost` which calls

`ViewsDelegate::ShouldCloseMenuIfMouseCaptureLost()` which then tries to

access `CaptureModeController` after its destruction.



Test: exo_unittests, ash_unittests

entry.title: [CloudOpenMetrics] Log TaskResult when user exits cloud upload\open flow
entry.content:
When the user tries to open a file with Google Docs or MS365, they will

be taken to the setup/fixup flow if extra setup is required. Previously,

if the user cancelled at the setup/fixup flow or instead chose a local

file task (not Google Docs or MS365) as the default task, no TaskResult

was logged, leading to inconsistent metrics [1].



Expand OfficeTaskResult with kCancelledAtSetup and kLocalFileTask to

use in these cases. Update ~CloudOpenMetrics() to check for these

consistencies.



[1] https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1496488
